*STORY FRAGMENTS:;
*a few points of variation in expectations is produced through psychology - specifically, savouring and optimism - but conditional on actual objective likelihood of success, self-esteem and LOC do not matter to expectation formation (pointing to the notion that higher SE or more internal LOC does not produce delusion - just more resources that can objectively produce success);
*stated risk aversion IS explained by locus of control (given finding above, this could be because the mental context in which the risk question is evaluated is different for high and low LOC people:  low-LOC people assume a situation that is less favourable, because that is what they are used to facing);
*higher expectations causally produce more risk-taking (staying in the betting game) but are NOT related to stated risk aversion;
*lock-in effect of amount wagered ("bet"), controlling for winpc, on dropout behavior;
*we replicate the standard results that men are more risk-taking - both behaviorally and using stated risk aversion - and, when we control for everything else, also have higher expectations of success;

      *OET_data_exam.do;
*do-file to analyse OET experimental data from the experiments run at UNSW in August/September 2010;

*QUESTIONS for Markus:
*to go into the userguide:  ;
    *subject 505 has only 15 race-by-pitstop obs, not 18 (why?);

*STORY FRAGMENTS:;
*a few points of variation in expectations is produced through psychology - specifically, savouring and optimism - but conditional on actual objective likelihood of success, self-esteem and LOC do not matter to expectation formation (pointing to the notion that higher SE or more internal LOC does not produce delusion - just more resources that can objectively produce success);
*stated risk aversion IS explained by locus of control (given finding above, this could be because the mental context in which the risk question is evaluated is different for high and low LOC people:  low-LOC people assume a situation that is less favourable, because that is what they are used to facing);
*higher expectations causally produce more risk-taking (staying in the betting game) but are NOT related to stated risk aversion;
*lock-in effect of amount wagered ("bet"), controlling for winpc, on dropout behavior;
*we replicate the standard results that men are more risk-taking - both behaviorally and using stated risk aversion - and, when we control for everything else, also have higher expectations of success;
